Class Keccak

java.lang.Object
  Keccak

public class Keccak
extends java.lang.Object

Class that implements the Keccak algorithm, as submitted to the SHA-3 final round, which it won. This implementation follows the Python reference from the authors of the algorithm closely. Please note, this class logs debugging info. If you need to access that information please use Log.set(Log.LEVEL_DEBUG).

See Also:
PIProvider, SHA3MessageDigest, Keccak website, Keccak Python reference implementation, The Keccak reference, Keccak implementation overview

paddingSimplified

private byte[] paddingSimplified(int length,

                                 int blockSize)
Calculates the padding of the message using follow the specification: P = M || 0x01 || 0x00 || … || 0x00 P = P xor (0x00 || … || 0x00 || 0x80) Note this only works for a message with a length divisible by 8.

Parameters:
length - length of the message
message - message to pad
Returns:
padded message

padding10star1

private byte[] padding10star1(int length,
                              byte[] message,
                              int blockSize)
Calculates the padded message using the 10*1 padding rule, or multi-rate padding. Note that the last byte has its bits shifted as in the specification for the SHA-3:
In practice, the above operation cancels with the change of convention, so there is nothing to do, except: • For the last byte if it contains p < 8 bits, the bits are shifted by 8 − p positions towards the LSB (i.e., to the "right").

Parameters:
length - length of the message
message - the message to pad
blockSize - the size of a block
Returns:
padded message
See Also:
The Keccak SHA-3 submission, 6.1 Bit and byte numbering

padMessage

Calculator for the padded message. We use two different padding rules. If the length of the message is divisible by 8 we use a simplification of the multi-rate padding rule, otherwise this rule is used.
